  "structural_observations": [
    "Origin and Resolution are universal bookends: every archetype begins with exactly one Origin node and ends with exactly one Resolution node.",
    "Crisis is structurally universal: all 15 archetypes contain at least one Crisis node. The Hero's Journey is the only archetype with two (The Ordeal and Resurrection).",
    "Disrupts order and restores equilibrium are the universal edge pair: 'disrupts order' opens all 15 archetypes; 'restores equilibrium' closes 14 of 15 (Coming of Age closes with 'enables transformation').",
    "Forces commitment is the most common non-universal edge meaning (13 instances across 11 archetypes), reflecting that most story structures require an irreversible commitment point.",
    "The Hero's Journey is the most structurally complex archetype with 12 nodes and 12 edges, including variant branches (Refusal of the Call) and doubled roles (two Crisis nodes, two Trial nodes).",
    "Three archetypes share the Irreversible Cost role — Tragedy, Coming of Age, and The Rise and Fall — identifying them as the archetypes where permanent loss is a structural node rather than an edge effect.",
    "The Reckoning role is assigned to The Revenge's Final Reckoning node (RV_N07), distinguishing it from the Crisis role used in other climactic confrontations.",
    "All 15 edge meanings in the controlled vocabulary are now assigned to at least one edge. 'compels return' is used in the Hero's Journey for the Reward-to-Road Back transition."
